The media type definition says what methods do.  In most cases there&#39;s
plenty of wiggle-room on response codes, so that&#39;s left to the API to
describe.  A system&#39;s security implementation isn&#39;t described by its
media types, so your API has to describe the use of HTTP Digest, user
roles, and such.  Your API does this via hypertext -- descriptive error
responses with links instead of the default 4xx response message, for
example.

-Eric

&gt; 
&gt; In [1] Roy writes
&gt; 
&gt; &quot;A REST API should spend almost all of its descriptive effort in  
&gt; defining the media type(s) used for representing resources and
&gt; driving application state, or in defining extended relation names
&gt; and/or hypertext-enabled mark-up for existing standard media types.
&gt; [...]&quot;
&gt; 
&gt; Maybe I am reading too much into this, but then...usually Roy
&gt; chooses his words quite carefully:
&gt; 
&gt; Does anyone know why it is &quot;*almost* all of its descriptive effort&quot;  
&gt; and not simply &quot;all of its descriptive effort&quot;? What else is there
&gt; to be described than the media types?
&gt; 
&gt; Jan
